more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":0,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":35,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth of Ashbourne was born in 1224, in Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England. She married Roger de Cokayne. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 3 daughters. She died about 1261, in her hometown, at the age of 38, and was buried in Ashbourne Circuit, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1224–about 1261":"1224–umbes 1261","1220–1300":"1220–1300","1240–1284":"1240–1284","1248–1324":"1248–1324","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1254–1301":"1254–1301","1258–1340":"1258–1340","–Female":"Surnud","1224–1261":"1224–1261","about 1250":"umbes 1250","about 1261":"umbes 1261","1220":"1220","Abt 1248":"umbes 1248","1340":"1340","1284":"1284","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1261":"1261","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1258":"1258","1324":"1324","1224":"1